    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-05-18T10:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-05-18T10:30:00-05:00" n="812"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d812">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00111 A.R./1093: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Uruguay</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Montevideo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-05-18T12:00:00-03:30"
                            >May 18, 1940—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 12:53 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>75. Guani has just telephoned me to say that Chile has accepted the Uruguayan
                    text (I advised him after learning from Panama that Nicaragua has also
                    accepted). He is therefore telegraphing Panama at once requesting that, as all
                    the American States have accepted, the protest be published by the President of
                    Panama in tomorrow morning’s papers. He intends to publish it here at that time
                    and hopes other governments will do the same. He also intends as author of the
                    initiative, to transmit the text to the Pope.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
